Review and Critique of the Book
Stephen Hawking's A Brief History of Time
Stephen Hawking's A Brief History of Time is a book that tries to make the most complicated ideas about the universe easy for everyone to understand. The ideas are very deep into the space and hard, even though they don't need any advanced studies. The book talks about how the universe started, how it works, and what might happen to it go through in the future. I felt both amazed and confused while reading it, which I think is what Hawking wanted—to make people question themselves.
Three Important Ideas Explained in My Own Words
1. The Big Bang and How the Universe Came to Be
The Big Bang theory is one of the main ideas in the book. Hawking says that the universe didn't always look like it does now. Instead, everything began at one very hot and dense point and then quickly was spread out. This growth made room for time, space, matter, and energy. The notion that time itself commenced at the Big Bang truly shook me. There was no "past" in the usual sense before that moment because time didn't exist yet.
2. Event Horizons and Black Holes
One of the most interesting parts of the book is about black holes. Hawking says that black holes happen when big stars fall apart because of their own gravity. The gravity gets so strong that even light can't go away from that gravity . The event horizon is the line that is used to mark  the edge of a black hole. Once something crosses it, it can never come back. Hawking's idea that black holes aren't completely black made this even more appealing to the readers . They slowly give off radiation (now called Hawking radiation) and can eventually disappear over time.
3. Time, Relativity, and What Reality Is
Time itself is another important idea. Hawking explains that time moves at different speeds in different places. Einstein's theory of relativity says that time slows down when there is a lot of gravity or when speeds are very high. This means that time isn't always the same. The notion that two individuals may perceive time differently based on their location or velocity significantly brought a change in my thinking about time ..
What I Didn't Get (Being Honest)
The book tries to make things easier, but there were still parts that I really didn't get. The idea of imaginary time was one of the hardest things to understand. Hawking uses math to explain it, but I don't know much about advanced math, so it was hard for me to understand what imaginary time really means in the real world. I also found quantum mechanics explanations hard to understand, especially when Hawking talks about particles coming and going out of nowhere. It's hard to accept these ideas logically because they go against what we know from our everyday life.
How This Relates to What I Learn in Physics Class
We learn a lot about motion, gravity, energy, and the structure of the universe in physics class, and this book is very related to that. We already learn about things like Newton's laws and gravity, but Hawking shows how they don't work as well when things are really big or really small. The idea of relativity has to do with lessons about time and speed, while black holes have to do with mass and gravity. The book goes way beyond what we have learnt  in class, but it helps me understand why physics is important and how what we learn in class fits into the universe.
Five Questions This Book Made Me Think About
What caused the Big Bang if time started at the Big Bang?
Are there limits to what people can know, or can we really  truly understand the universe?
What really happens goes on inside  a black hole after the event horizon?
Where does all the information that is inside that black hole go if black holes can disappear?
Is there any one theory that can explain everything that happens in the universe?
